**Abstract class vs Interface** â€” dono ka use similar lagta hai, par kaafi **deep differences** hote hain.

---

## ğŸ§  Abstract Class vs Interface in Java (Hinglish + Deep Comparison)

| Feature                     | **Abstract Class**                                        | **Interface**                                           |
|-----------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------|
| âœ… Purpose                  | Partial abstraction (some implemented, some abstract)     | Pure abstraction (Java 7 tak only abstract methods)     |
| ğŸ”‘ Keyword                  | `abstract class ClassName`                               | `interface InterfaceName`                               |
| ğŸ“¦ Inheritance              | Ek hi abstract class inherit kar sakte ho (single)        | Multiple interfaces implement kar sakte ho âœ…           |
| ğŸ§± Constructors             | âœ… Allowed (constructor for base initialization)          | âŒ Not allowed                                           |
| ğŸ§ª Method Types             | Abstract + Non-abstract methods allowed                   | Only abstract (Java 7), + default & static (Java 8+)    |
| ğŸ” Access Modifiers (methods) | `public`, `protected`, `private` allowed                 | Only `public` (by default)                              |
| ğŸ§Š Fields                   | Instance vars (non-static) bhi allowed                    | Only `public static final` (constants) by default       |
| ğŸ§¬ Multiple Inheritance     | âŒ Not supported                                           | âœ… Supported                                             |
| ğŸ— Use Case                | When base class needs partial logic                       | When only contracts/structure define karna ho           |

---

## ğŸ” Quick Example Comparison:

### âœ… Abstract Class Example:

```java
abstract class Animal {
    String name;

    Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    abstract void sound(); // no body

    void sleep() {
        System.out.println(name + " is sleeping.");
    }
}
```

---

### âœ… Interface Example:

```java
interface Animal {
    void sound(); // abstract
    default void sleep() {
        System.out.println("Sleeping...");
    }
}
```

---

## ğŸ¯ Kab Abstract Class use kare?

âœ… Jab:
- Common fields chahiye (like `name`, `age`, etc.)
- Partial behavior common karna ho (some logic in base class)
- Constructor ke through initial setup chahiye

---

## ğŸ¯ Kab Interface use kare?

âœ… Jab:
- Sirf behavior define karna ho (what, not how)
- Multiple behaviors chahiye (like `Flyable`, `Drivable`)
- Loose coupling & abstraction banana ho (design patterns etc.)

---

## ğŸ§  Real-World Analogy:

| Scenario         | Abstract Class                        | Interface                            |
|------------------|----------------------------------------|--------------------------------------|
| Parent + child   | Ek parent jisme kuch default rules     | Contract jisko koi bhi follow kar sakta hai |
| Template         | Basic structure + kuch ready logic     | Sirf headings, implementation alag   |
| Example          | `Vehicle` class (base)                 | `Flyable`, `Eatable`, `Playable`     |

---

## ğŸ”¥ Combo use bhi hota hai

```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    abstract void start();
}

interface Electric {
    void charge();
}

class Tesla extends Vehicle implements Electric {
    void start() { System.out.println("Tesla started."); }
    public void charge() { System.out.println("Charging..."); }
}
```

---

Bhai agar tu bole toh main ek full mini project bana deta hoon jisme `abstract class + interface` dono ka use ho â€” like `Vehicle`, `Car`, `Bike`, `Electric`, `Petrol` etc.

